description:
drh added on 2019-11-15 00:06:15:
Table valued functions do not work as the right-hand table of a LEFT JOIN.
The arguments to the table valued function become constraints on the HIDDEN
columns of the virtual table in the WHERE clause, whereas they should be
constraints in the ON clause for a LEFT JOIN.  Because the constraints are
on the WHERE clause rather than the ON clause, the join acts like a INNER JOIN.
The following code illustrates the problem:
CREATE TABLE t1(x);
INSERT INTO t1 VALUES('a'),('b'),('c');
SELECT x, value FROM t1 LEFT JOIN json_each('["b"]') ON x=value;
The output is a single row, which is exactly what one would expect if the
LEFT keyword were omitted.  This is because the parser rewrites the
query as follows:
CREATE TABLE t1(x);
INSERT INTO t1 VALUES('a'),('b'),('c');
SELECT x, value FROM t1 LEFT JOIN json_each ON x=value WHERE json='["b"]';
Reformulating the query like this:
CREATE TABLE t1(x);
INSERT INTO t1 VALUES('a'),('b'),('c');
SELECT x, value FROM t1 LEFT JOIN json_each ON x=value AND json='["b"]';
Gives the expected result.
This problem has existed in the code ever since table-valued functions were
added in version 3.9.0 (2015-10-14).
